    "summary": "The State of Qi (475–221 BC) was one of the most powerful of the seven major states of the [[event:1111|Warring States Period]], located in the northeast of China (modern Shandong), renowned as a center of intellectual culture through its Jixia Academy and as a major commercial and military power.\n\nQi was geographically advantaged with fertile agricultural land, access to sea salt, and extensive coastline enabling trade. The Jixia Academy (c. 318–221 BC), established by the Qi court, was perhaps the most remarkable intellectual institution of ancient China, hosting scholars from all philosophical schools — Confucians, Daoists, Legalists, and others — in an early model of state-sponsored intellectual debate. Major thinkers including Mencius (a key Confucian), Zou Yan (cosmological theorist), and Xunzi spent time at the Jixia Academy. Qi's military power made it a rival to Qin for dominance over China, but internal instability and successive defeats by Qin's superior military organization led to its conquest by Qin in 221 BC, the last major state to fall.",
